description.text: Print your own house or padlock key with this easy to use key generator

Warning! - this is for printing a PLASTIC key.  This key is optimized for printing at 0.30mm layers, and is only 7 layers thick!!!  Although it works fine - it is plastic - and can / will break off if you are not careful!  With that in mind, you simply need to enter in an appropriate code for your key, and select the style of key you want to print.  You may want to have a nail file on hand, to remove any extra bits of plastic first.  Leave the code number blank, to generate a random key.  I would love to see copies that anyone prints - however - BEWARE - you might not want to post a working copy of your house key - someone else might print one too!
If you hold the key in your left hand, with the blade pointing to the right, the KeyCutCode reads from left to right. 0 for no cut up to 9 for a maximum cut. You can switch to the 'top' view in 'customizer', and hold your key in front of the screen while you adjust the values. It may take a couple of prints to find just the right match, fortunately it doesn't take long to print, and doesn't use up a whole lot of your filament. You might want to print your first try using the 'straight' key header, to save even more time / filament!

title: Tantillus dowel mount for loose filament

description.text:
Put a horizontal dowel on a printed case Tantillus for holding loose filament.  
This takes the place of the spacer washers on the front stiffener just like the side fan mounts.  Any sort of 5/16" or 8mm rod can be used, but wood dowels seem to be a good option as they're cheap and will probably break before the mount will.  The dowel is friction fit so that it can be easily removed for travel.  
SCAD provided so you can change up the dowel hole size or use it as a base for mounting other stuff to a printed Tantillus.

1) Print as oriented
2) Replace the washers with the mount on the front stiffener so that the dowel mount sits on top of the stiffener
3) Insert 5/16" or 8mm dowel in the hole. Can be as long as you wish
4) Space two binder clips arms-up to keep the filament on the dowel
5) Put your filament coil between the clips and load the end into the Tantillus
6) Print more stuff

title: Pilot Headset Boom Mike Attachment for Headphones

description.text: This is the washer and cap with channels for attaching a bent wire and machine screw mic boom to hard shell headphones to make something similar to my good David Clark aviation headset.  I made this so my boy could have a headset for his pilot costume without risking my $300 headset.  Afterwards I will have a comfortable but very tough Skype/VOIP headset for the computer where the mike securely folds out of the way when watching movies or listening to music.

Using two pliers and a narrow shaft phillips screwdriver I bent clothes hangar wire first into a squared U with loops at the end for the section boom attached with this printable part to hard shell headphones. Then made second part by wrapping around the screwdriver shaft bending at the wrapped section with 90 degree angles, the other ends have loops for attaching the David Clark mic or like I did a cheap computer mic.
You attach the first U section that will later be snapped into the printed parts to the second wrapped section by taking a M3 25mm screw, adding a M3 washer, inserting through the first loop of the U section, adding another M3 washer, inserting into the wrapped wire section, another M3 washer, the other loop of the U section, a last M3 washer, and then a lock NUT tightened enough to make the mic boom stiff but adjustable.
Print the two plastic parts (10% size them both) and allow to cool so they don't warp when snapped together. Put the cap with the cutout for the bent wire mic boom on top insert the mic boom, then snap the plastic washer onto the extension of the cap. Evaluate where drilling and installation will not damage the headphones(not my fault if you break them) and where it wont block size adjustment, the boom should also be set low enough to reach your mouth. Drill a hole for a M3 25mm screw wherever you decide is best on the headphones. Open the headphone cup and drill outwards. Insert the screw from the inside out through a M3 washer, then out through the hole in the headphone cup. Place the mic boom/printed parts assembly onto the screw, than add a M3 washer, tighten down a lock nut until the boom is the right stiffness to adjust and stay.
This does not match the quality of a Clark headset but it looks good on a kid and I plan to use it for Skype when needed. Had I tried harder with measurements and wraps and used stiff stainless vs the low grade recycled scrap steel hanger wire I am not sure you could see much difference from the DC mic boom.
I included a comparison shot of the DIY headset and the David Clarks for comparison, also the .scad files so you can mod them with OpenSCAD.
I wouldn't use this for flying as the regular 8ohm music earphones don't block engine noise, though you might try adding speakers and this boom mic to earmuff hearing protectors if you are trying to save cash while taking flight lessons or building a DIY experimental or ultralight airplane.

description.text: Since the first Radial Engine was built in 1901, the technology has been synonymous with aviation. The first flight across the English Channel was powered by a 3-cylinder 12 hp radial engine, built by Italian engine designer Alessandro Anzani. The heavy bombers of the Second World War were powered by massive 28-cylinder 4,300 hp radial monsters from Pratt & Whitney. Radial engines have largely been supplanted in aviation by gas turbines, but are still found today on specialized acrobatic aircraft. This 5-Cylinder Radial Engine Model is based on the Forest Edwards Radial 5, a radial model aircraft engine. This engine started from excellent paper plans drawn by Robert Sigler. The engine described in RobertsÃÂ¢Ã¢ÂÂ¬Ã¢ÂÂ¢s plans is intended to be machined form metal, and had to be extensively modified to work with desktop 3D printing technology. Designed for use in a dark room, this small globe is lit by a 9v Battery and LEDs from the inside to act as your own starry night sky to keep on your desk.
NOTE: I have not printed or tested this item yet. I don't know how feasible the supports may be or if the star holes work out to be the right size. So far I mostly just uploaded this to remind myself to print it out later. Afterwards I will update whatever info I can. Regarding the LED circuit: What I had in mind was to put 9V batteries that have fallen below ideal 9 volts to use powering some LEDs until their charge runs out (or very low). So, in my case, I'll be using about 3-4 white and/or blue LEDs soldered together in series with a resistor to limit the current. If you're unfamiliar with this kind of circuit, all you need to do is connect your LEDs together in series and then add a resistor in series (tutorials for this all over the internet if you want to understand it better.) To pick your resistor you need to know the voltage drop of your LED(s) (different colors = different voltage drops) and then pick a resistor that gives you a current between around 10-30mA (or whatever works for your LEDs) using Ohm's Law, V=IR.

description.text:
This is a tie. It is made from panels. Each panels are connected with flexible connector featuring living hinges/springs. There are 3 hinges with different thickness. Their thickness are:
  • Flexconn rev.0 with 0.03125" thick spring
  • Flexconn rev.1 with 0.03500" thick spring
  • Flexconn rev.2 with 0.03800" thick spring
  • Flexconn rev.3 with 0.04000" thick spring
    • There are actually 4, aren't there?! These Flexconn do break a lot. So print as many as you can for spare parts. When these Flexconns break, the Flexible Sheet will prevent tie breakage. Flexible Sheet can printed in transparency paper on any color plastic sheet to further accent the look. These Flexible sheet and Flexconn are fastened to the panels with 4 pieces of 4-40 countersunk machine screws that are 1/8" long. There are seven of them on a tie, 28 totals screws. Here's a link to order the semi standard screw:
    https://www.boltdepot.com/Product-Details.aspx?product=9714 As far as printing the panel. The panel will look better and probly print faster if you orient the build vertically. During print arrangements, please ensure that the observe/front surface of the panel are facing outward. This is to ensure tie's observe surface quality. (ie. no filament drag/hair. See Toolpath and filament drag/hair picture) The Flexconn are better printed flat. So if you want to print the Panels and the Flexconn together with different color, just make sure you float the Panel above the Flexconn. That way only the support for the panel come out with 2 colors. Anyway play around with the printer orientation. I'm sure you guys and gals will figure it out. This tie is 19inches long. If you are 5ft 3in to 5ft 8in, you're fine. Add 3 inches of tie length for every 6 inches of body height. So scale accordingly and uniformly. Please remember to scale the Flexconn and Flexible Sheet as well. Btw, the design was inspired by "Sweet As!" Tie from "made in Jupiter". Here's the link to the blog about it:
    http://www.madeonjupiter.com/sweet-as/ Cheers,
    Peter

description.text:
This is a 1/72 scale model of a fictional 8 wheeled A.F.V. When printed, with glue and labor, it builds, a rolling car toy or can be finished for display or gaming purposes. This was my first design and far from easy to print or build, even as a master model builder I found it difficult. I have designed this vehicle for ease filing and sanding of hard plastic as well as to optimize customization with detail parts through "kit bashing" (use of parts from existing plastic model kits).
Assembly is difficult! This model is better suited for experienced builders, makers and gamers. The Mk.III (Chinchilla) offers a much improved print and easy assembly. Don't worry the Mk.IV is on the way.
A functional Mk.II model can be built from the first three files, but warped corners from printing may lead to difficulties in fit; therefore, the "new hull" from the fourth file was developed to address this issue. Also, the cylinder below the turret is too tall and will need to be cut down or modified, in addition the axles are too long and need to be shortened. The hull needs a support structure, the wheels do not and it is difficult to remove.
After much sanding and three coats of primer I finally got a smooth finish. I had trouble printing really small parts like, hatches and details, so used model kit parts. I airbrushed the model and used the HD stencil system from Anarchy Models for the Hex camo pattern. The paint job turned out well and the stencils are a really great product.

comments.text: Hello is there a sty for the hug and hatches  :)
comments.author: walkaboutgamez

comments.text: No, I need to rework this whole design. Hatches and detail accessories are on the list of things to fix and add.  This was my first design, you may have a lot better luck with some of the newer designs like the MK.III and Mk.IV, they are a lot more printer friendly, and less post production work.
comments.author: walkaboutgamez

comments.text: To achieve a smooth finish  I start  with a heavy mill file, then move to smaller files. I fill in problem areas with super glue and or modeling putty, then more filing. I then use a series of sanding sticks that started out as medium grit and go to super fine. The design also plays a part as simple geometry make it easier to file and sand. After all of that I spray several coats of primmer, I use the Tamiya Fine Surface Primer, normally I don't use anything out of a spray can, but this paint is awesome, you can spay it on pretty thick and it will flatten out when dry, it also sands well. It is expensive paint, but worth it and is available at any hobby shop. I hope that this will be helpful.

description.text:
What is an IcosaLEDron? It's a programmable, rechargeable 20 sided "ball" with a tri-color LED on each face. Inside is a custom PCB equipped with the Atmega328p and is Arduino compatible allowing for easy programming of different effects. With twenty WS2812B LEDs (also known as Neopixels) positioned equally around, and a 3-axis accelerometer, the IcosaLEDron is a spherical platform for creating light effects based on accelerations applied to the ball.
With the IcosaLEDron, we hope to excite makers and programmers to build there own, create and share custom codes, and help build a community of happy owners.
Visit our Instructables tutorial for much more information: http://www.instructables.com/id/IcosaLEDron-A-Multi-LED-Smart-Ball/

Included here are files for printing the rigid plastic pieces in ABS or PLA, and the rubber outer which we print with NinjaFlex Water (semi-transparent) thermoplastic elastomer (TPE) filament.
All parts are printable flat side down and without supports. NinjaFlex may be difficult to use on some printers. To address this we have been experimenting with casting the piece in transparent rubber.

Eric Gill, Ecstasy, 1910-1 This sculpture was owned by the collector Edward Perry Warren, of Lewes, Sussex, who also commissioned Rodin to make him 'The Kiss'. Gill carved the relief over a period of seven months, and called it 'They'. The title of 'Ecstasy' emerged after his death. When making this work, Gill was strongly influenced by Indian temple sculptures, which often showed couples in the act of copulation. Gill's sculpture, like that found on Indian temples, had a spiritual content. He wrote that 'All creative acts have God for their author. The human act of begetting is a type of divine creative power'. Gill titled a drawing for this work 'Christ and the Church'. tate.org.uk/art/artworks/gill-ecstasy-t03477

description.text:
The suggested mounting method for the electronics board of the Velleman K8200 is both unstable and risky. The board is mounted with two screws through the edge of the board. If the board case it hit by something it is likely that the PCB will break clean off, which would be catastrophic.
I have constructed a mount that solves the problem. The mount is bolted to the printer frame using the usual method of square nuts and M5 bolts. The electronics board is then fastened to the mount using four M3 bolts. The result is a safe and reliable installation of the electronics board.
I divided the mount into two parts to make it easy to print; a mounting plate and a rail. The rail fits between the plate and the aluminium frame to provide stability. It is not necessary to glue the parts together since they are held together by the M5 mounting bolts.
The long m3 bolts in the picture are 25 mm. I did not have anything more fitting available when I test fitted the board. 15 mm would have been perfect. The mounting plate has to be printed on a rather high infill to be stable enough. I recommend something like 70-75% infill.

description.text:
UPDATE 07/09/2015: I've uploaded version 3a which has a slightly increased cutout size as version 3 required some scrapping of material away to properly fit through. Printed and tested fine. I'm also going to generate a version (essentially the negative of this one) that can be used to cutout the shape from a generic case. Will make that a new thing rather than add to this one. Look out for it soon... +++++++
I bought a power socket from Jaycar (Part Num PP4003) for my hotwire cutter powerbox and got home only to realise I needed some way of mounting it as my plywood case walls are too thick.
This plate is a collar that goes over the socket and the socket snaps hold onto a lip inside the collar. The lip has been reinforced to some extent to avoid breaking when you pull the plug out. Time will tell if it works. You then mount the whole thing into the wall cutout of your box or case.
Openscad file is provided so you can adjust the outer size of the collar or thickness etc.
Tolerance on my printer is a little loose so I did have to scrape out a but of plastic from the inside edges to fit.
I did not create mounting holes. These are pretty easy to create while screwdriving or drilling anyway.
Print it out and push it over your socket, till the snaps...well...snap into place.

description.text:
UPDATE:
Some modifications to this part:
  • extra magnet mount in the bottom
  • mounting holes for the Octave Temperature Control/Switch.

The Nema 14 in the extruder head of the Up! Mini gets a little too hot with bigger projects. This mod adds a high efficiency fan to the motor to have it running cooler.
I repurposed a fan from some broken electronics I had lying around.
The casing/duct holds securely to the stepper motor with 4 small neodymium magnets (6mm/0.2" diameter) and it can be completely removed by simply disconnecting it from the JST connector.
The design adds very little weight to the extruder and works flawlessly.

I printed it in .25, normal speed, 10% infill, 3 layers. Raft and minimal support (settings may vary from printer to printer).
To secure it to the stepper motor there are mounts for four small 6mm (0.2") diameter neodymium magnets. Just glue the magnets in place and you are good to go.
For the bottom magnet mount you just have to slide it into place and it should require no gluing.

Why do this? I am using a DVD just as a round shape, mounted on a stepper motor shaft, with an optical mouse looking at a strip of paper wrapped around the rim as a shaft encoder. This is to measure the rotation angle, to calibrate a microstepping driver. The python code to read data from a USB mouse is also included (on Debian Linux, anyway). My mouse has some drift over time, so this is not a good absolute angle encoder, but good enough for what I wanted.
